Project Information:
- Title: Autonomous AI Agents for Spacecraft Operations
- Description: This research proposal focuses on developing autonomous AI agents for spacecraft operations, specifically in Guidance, Navigation, and Control (GNC) and Attitude and Orbit Control Systems (AOCS), as well as remote sensing. The vision is to create AI-driven agents capable of real-time communication with spacecraft systems and autonomously managing and controlling spacecraft functions. The objectives include reducing human involvement in mission-critical tasks, minimizing human error, and enhancing mission efficiency and safety. The proposal outlines expected technical innovations, such as improved AI reliability, decision-making under uncertainty, and seamless system integration. Challenges to address include ensuring AI reliability, effective decision-making under uncertainty, and successful system integration. The potential impacts on the space exploration industry include increased mission efficiency, safety, and reduced operational costs.
- Abstract: The Autonomous AI Agents for Spacecraft Operations project aims to revolutionize space exploration by integrating artificial intelligence (AI) into spacecraft operations, enhancing autonomy, efficiency, and decision-making capabilities. The project focuses on leveraging AI and machine learning (ML) to enable spacecraft to adapt to changing conditions, make real-time decisions, and operate with minimal human intervention, thus reducing communication delays and increasing mission precision. AI agents differ from traditional control systems by providing real-time decision-making, fault tolerance, and autonomous control, which are crucial for managing unforeseen situations and optimizing mission objectives. Machine learning plays a pivotal role in developing AI agents, enabling data analysis, pattern recognition, and low-latency predictions essential for next-generation missions. The project addresses challenges such as cybersecurity, ethical considerations, and data privacy, ensuring AI systems are robust, secure, and aligned with ethical guidelines. Training and validation processes involve continuous validation and certification to ensure AI models' reliability in space environments. The project collaborates with various partners to advance AI technologies, emphasizing the importance of explainability, certification, and ethical frameworks in AI deployment. Overall, the project seeks to expand the boundaries of autonomous space missions, facilitating scientific advancements and exploration initiatives.

